    {
        "user": "UA14TGLTC",
        "type": "message",
        "ts": "1770623556.369639",
        "client_msg_id": "a5a035e9-532e-40e6-8c7d-acf79bc0abd9",
        "text": "<@U02U0AS3J49> Instead of writing controlled language for LLMs, I let them do it.  I'm not interested in prompt engineering, so I'll give them a task with tests, usually they write the tests, and then its up to them to optimize.  Example, working on a Cluade skill that calls a bunch of different models in some fairly complicated ways; anyhow, this is a diff from earlier today.  Their change, not mine:\n&gt;       101 -3. Present all responses: Claude's answer first, then each external model's response\n&gt;       101 +3. Present all responses verbatim: Claude's answer first, then each external model's full unedited response. Do NOT summarize or\n&gt;           +paraphrase — show exactly what each model wrote.\nI'm still not good at this though.  In as much as good imperative programming, functional programming, and logic programming feel very different from one another, I think good LLM-based programming is new beast.",
        "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "source_team": "T5TCAFTA9",
        "user_profile": {
            "avatar_hash": "gae6d55db9d1",
            "image_72": "https:\/\/secure.gravatar.com\/avatar\/3ae6d55db9d15b79bc683a8031fc2588.jpg?s=72&d=https%3A%2F%2Fa.slack-edge.com%2Fdf10d%2Fimg%2Favatars%2Fava_0009-72.png",
            "first_name": "",
            "real_name": "William Taysom",
            "display_name": "wtaysom",
            "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
            "name": "wtaysom",
            "is_restricted": false,
            "is_ultra_restricted": false
        },
        "thread_ts": "1770333930.325449",
        "parent_user_id": "UGWUJUZHT",
        "blocks": [
            {
                "type": "rich_text",
                "block_id": "B+Y4c",
                "elements": [
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "user",
                                "user_id": "U02U0AS3J49"
                            },
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": " Instead of writing controlled language for LLMs, I let them do it.  I'm not interested in prompt engineering, so I'll give them a task with tests, usually they write the tests, and then its up to them to optimize.  Example, working on a Cluade skill that calls a bunch of different models in some fairly complicated ways; anyhow, this is a diff from earlier today.  Their change, not mine:\n"
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_quote",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "      101 -3. Present all responses: Claude's answer first, then each external model's response\n      101 +3. Present all responses verbatim: Claude's answer first, then each external model's full unedited response. Do NOT summarize or\n          +paraphrase — show exactly what each model wrote."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "type": "rich_text_section",
                        "elements": [
                            {
                                "type": "text",
                                "text": "I'm still not good at this though.  In as much as good imperative programming, functional programming, and logic programming feel very different from one another, I think good LLM-based programming is new beast."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    }
